{
  "sentences": [
    {
      "explanation": "In Spanish, greetings often combine \"hola\" with the time of day. \"Buenos\" is masculine plural to match \"días\" (days), unlike English which doesn't change adjectives to match nouns.",
      "sentence": "Hola, buenos días",
      "translation": "Hello, good morning"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "\"Buenas noches\" is used for both \"good evening\" and \"good night\" in Spanish. Notice it uses \"buenas\" (feminine) because \"noche\" is a feminine noun, unlike \"días\".",
      "sentence": "Buenas noches",
      "translation": "Good evening"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Use this greeting from midday until sunset. Like \"buenas noches\", it uses the feminine \"buenas\" to match the feminine noun \"tardes\" (afternoons).",
      "sentence": "Buenas tardes",
      "translation": "Good afternoon"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Instead of saying \"my name is\" like in English, Spanish speakers usually say \"me llamo\", which literally translates to \"I call myself\".",
      "sentence": "Hola, me llamo Ana",
      "translation": "Hello, my name is Ana"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Spanish questions require an upside-down question mark (¿) at the beginning. \"Cómo\" literally means \"how\", so you are actually asking \"how do you call yourself?\".",
      "sentence": "¿Cómo te llamas?",
      "translation": "What is your name?"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "This is the most common way to say \"nice to meet you\" when introduced to someone. It literally translates to \"much pleasure\".",
      "sentence": "Mucho gusto",
      "translation": "Nice to meet you"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "You can combine standard farewells and expressions of gratitude naturally. \"Gracias\" is the standard way to say thank you in all Spanish-speaking regions.",
      "sentence": "Adiós, gracias",
      "translation": "Goodbye, thank you"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Adding \"muchas\" before \"gracias\" turns it into \"thank you very much\". Notice that \"muchas\" ends in \"-as\" to match the feminine plural word \"gracias\".",
      "sentence": "Muchas gracias, adiós",
      "translation": "Thank you very much, goodbye"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "sentences": [
    {
      "explanation": "In French, you must use the partitive article 'du' (some) when asking for an unspecified amount of a masculine noun like 'pain', rather than just saying the word for bread on its own.",
      "sentence": "Je voudrais du pain, s'il vous plaît.",
      "translation": "I would like some bread, please."
    },
    {
      "explanation": "It is a strong cultural tradition in France to eat cheese ('le fromage') after the main course and before dessert. Notice the use of 'du' to mean 'some cheese'.",
      "sentence": "Nous mangeons du fromage après le repas.",
      "translation": "We eat cheese after the meal."
    },
    {
      "explanation": "In English, you ask for a 'wine list', but in French, it translates literally to a 'menu of the wines' (carte des vins). The word 'carte' is used for the menu you order from.",
      "sentence": "Avez-vous une carte des vins ?",
      "translation": "Do you have a wine list?"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "The adjective 'chaude' has an 'e' at the end because 'soupe' is a feminine noun. In French, adjectives must agree in gender with the noun they describe.",
      "sentence": "La soupe est très chaude.",
      "translation": "The soup is very hot."
    },
    {
      "explanation": "'Quel' means 'what' or 'which' and is used here to ask about a specific masculine noun ('le dessert'). The phrase 'du jour' literally means 'of the day'.",
      "sentence": "Quel est le dessert du jour ?",
      "translation": "What is the dessert of the day?"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "In English, we often say 'I will have' when ordering food. In French, the verb 'prendre' (to take) is most commonly used in the present tense to order food at a restaurant.",
      "sentence": "Je prends la soupe et un dessert.",
      "translation": "I will have the soup and a dessert."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "sentences": [
    {
      "explanation": "In German, possessive words like 'my' change endings based on the gender of the noun. Because 'Mutter' (mother) is feminine, you must use 'meine' ending in '-e'.",
      "sentence": "Das ist meine Mutter",
      "translation": "That is my mother"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Because 'Vater' (father) is masculine, the word for 'my' is 'mein' without an extra ending. Additionally, German uses the word 'groß' (big) to say someone is tall.",
      "sentence": "Mein Vater ist groß",
      "translation": "My father is tall"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "To ask a yes/no question in German, you put the verb ('hast') at the beginning of the sentence. 'Bruder' uses 'einen' instead of 'ein' because it is the direct object (accusative case).",
      "sentence": "Hast du einen Bruder?",
      "translation": "Do you have a brother?"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "German doesn't have an '-ing' continuous form like English. The single verb 'lernt' translates to both 'learns' and 'is learning'.",
      "sentence": "Meine Schwester lernt Deutsch",
      "translation": "My sister is learning German"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Notice that all nouns in German, including 'Familie', are always capitalized. Like in American English, 'Familie' is a singular collective noun, so it takes the singular verb 'ist'.",
      "sentence": "Die Familie ist sehr groß",
      "translation": "The family is very large"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "sentences": [
    {
      "explanation": "These are the numbers 一 (ichi), 二 (ni), and 三 (san). The characters are easy to remember because they are simply one, two, and three horizontal lines.",
      "sentence": "一、二、三",
      "translation": "One, two, three"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "一つ (hitotsu) is the general counting word for \"one thing.\" When ordering or asking for something, you state the quantity followed directly by ください (kudasai), meaning \"please.\"",
      "sentence": "一つください",
      "translation": "One, please"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "二つ (futatsu) means \"two things.\" Adding です (desu) at the end makes it a polite sentence indicating \"It is two\" or \"There are two.\" Unlike English, Japanese attaches specific counter words like つ (tsu) to numbers depending on what is being counted.",
      "sentence": "二つです",
      "translation": "There are two"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Here we have 三 (san) for three, 五 (go) for five, and 十 (juu) for ten. In Japanese, items in a list are often separated by a comma-like punctuation mark called a tōten (、).",
      "sentence": "三、五、十",
      "translation": "Three, five, ten"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "五つ (itsutsu) combines the number five, 五 (go), with the general counter つ (tsu). You would use this exact phrase when asking a shopkeeper for five of the same item.",
      "sentence": "五つください",
      "translation": "Five, please"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "To say \"and\" when connecting nouns or numbers, Japanese uses the particle と (to). So 五 (go) and 十 (juu) naturally become 五と十 (go to juu).",
      "sentence": "五と十",
      "translation": "Five and ten"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "sentences": [
    {
      "explanation": "In Korean, color words often end with 색 (saek), which literally means \"color.\" So, 빨간색 (ppalgansaek) means \"red color,\" and is used with the verb 이에요 (ieyo) meaning \"is.\"",
      "sentence": "사과는 빨간색이에요",
      "translation": "The apple is red"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "바다 (bada) means \"ocean\" or \"sea.\" Notice how the subject marker 가 (ga) is attached to 바다, marking it as the subject of the sentence before the color 파란색 (paransaek).",
      "sentence": "바다가 파란색이에요",
      "translation": "The ocean is blue"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "When describing an object, place the color word before the noun, just like in English. 노란색 (noransaek) comes directly before 우산 (usan), which means \"umbrella.\"",
      "sentence": "노란색 우산을 샀어요",
      "translation": "I bought a yellow umbrella"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "초록색 (choroksaek) means \"green.\" 제가 좋아하는 색 (jega joahaneun saek) is a common phrase meaning \"my favorite color\" or literally \"the color I like.\"",
      "sentence": "제가 좋아하는 색은 초록색이에요",
      "translation": "My favorite color is green"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "고양이 (goyangi) means \"cat.\" Instead of just using a lone adjective for \"black,\" Korean typically describes objects by saying they \"are a black color\" using 검은색 (geomeunsaek) followed by the \"to be\" verb.",
      "sentence": "그 고양이는 검은색이에요",
      "translation": "That cat is black"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "sentences": [
    {
      "explanation": "Em italiano, usa-se a preposição \"per\" (para) para indicar o destino de uma viagem, muito parecido com o português. A palavra \"stazione\" é feminina, por isso usamos o artigo \"la\".",
      "sentence": "Il treno per Roma parte dalla stazione centrale.",
      "translation": "O trem para Roma parte da estação central."
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Em português dizemos \"passagem\" ou \"bilhete\" para viagens, mas em italiano usa-se \"biglietto\" para qualquer tipo de entrada, seja passagem de avião, bilhete de trem ou ingresso de cinema.",
      "sentence": "Dove posso comprare il biglietto?",
      "translation": "Onde posso comprar a passagem?"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Ao contrário do português, que usa a preposição \"de\" para meios de transporte (de carro, de trem), o italiano geralmente usa a preposição \"in\": \"in macchina\", \"in treno\".",
      "sentence": "Preferiamo viaggiare in macchina.",
      "translation": "Nós preferimos viajar de carro."
    },
    {
      "explanation": "A palavra \"aereo\" começa com vogal, então o artigo masculino \"il\" sofre elisão e se torna \"l'\". Para expressar horas, o italiano usa a preposição articulada \"alle\" (às).",
      "sentence": "L'aereo arriva alle otto di sera.",
      "translation": "O avião chega às oito da noite."
    },
    {
      "explanation": "A contração \"all'\" é a junção da preposição \"a\" com o artigo \"l'\". Em italiano, os verbos de movimento geralmente pedem a preposição \"a\" (vai all'aeroporto) em vez de \"para\", que é comum no Brasil.",
      "sentence": "L'autobus va all'aeroporto?",
      "translation": "O ônibus vai para o aeroporto?"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "O adjetivo \"lontano\" (longe) deve concordar em gênero com o sujeito. Como \"stazione\" é feminino, usamos \"lontana\". Além disso, \"longe de\" traduz-se como \"lontano da\".",
      "sentence": "La stazione non è lontana da qui.",
      "translation": "A estação não é longe daqui."
    },
    {
      "explanation": "O verbo \"hai\" (tens/você tem) não precisa ser acompanhado do pronome \"tu\", pois a desinência verbal já indica o sujeito, algo que o português também faz com frequência (sujeito oculto).",
      "sentence": "Hai il biglietto per il treno?",
      "translation": "Você tem a passagem para o trem?"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "sentences": [
    {
      "explanation": "Em espanhol, usa-se \"¿Cuánto cuesta?\" para perguntar o preço de algo. Note que o espanhol exige o uso do ponto de interrogação invertido (¿) no início da pergunta, um sinal de pontuação que não existe no português.",
      "sentence": "¿Cuánto cuesta esta camisa?",
      "translation": "Quanto custa esta camisa?"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "A palavra \"tienda\" significa \"loja\" em espanhol. É um falso cognato para os falantes de português, que podem associar a palavra a uma \"tenda\" de lona ou acampamento. O adjetivo \"cara\" concorda em gênero com o substantivo.",
      "sentence": "Esta tienda es muy cara",
      "translation": "Esta loja é muito cara"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "A palavra \"barato\" escreve-se e tem o mesmo significado que em português. O contraste principal está no verbo \"Quiero\" (Quero), que sofre uma ditongação (a letra 'e' muda para 'ie'), uma característica comum em verbos no espanhol.",
      "sentence": "Quiero comprar un celular barato",
      "translation": "Quero comprar um celular barato"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "A palavra \"precio\" é quase idêntica ao nosso \"preço\", mas é escrita com 'c', já que o espanhol não utiliza a cedilha (ç). Além disso, perguntas em espanhol sempre abrem e fecham com sinais de interrogação.",
      "sentence": "¿Cuál es el precio de los zapatos?",
      "translation": "Qual é o preço dos sapatos?"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Para comparar preços, o espanhol utiliza a estrutura \"más [adjetivo] que\", de forma perfeitamente equivalente ao nosso \"mais [adjetivo] que\". A palavra \"caro\" também é usada exatamente da mesma forma nas duas línguas.",
      "sentence": "Este vestido es más caro que el otro",
      "translation": "Este vestido é mais caro que o outro"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "No comércio hispânico, usa-se a palavra \"tarjeta\" para dizer \"cartão\". A letra 'j' em espanhol tem um som aspirado forte na garganta, que soa bastante diferente do 'j' do português. A frase também omite o pronome \"eles\", indo direto ao verbo \"Aceptan\".",
      "sentence": "¿Aceptan tarjeta de crédito en esta tienda?",
      "translation": "Aceitam cartão de crédito nesta loja?"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "sentences": [
    {
      "explanation": "En francés, para hablar de la temperatura ambiental se usa el verbo \"faire\" (hacer) con el pronombre impersonal \"il\". Literalmente se construye como \"él hace calor\".",
      "sentence": "Il fait très chaud en été",
      "translation": "Hace mucho calor en verano"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Al igual que en español decimos \"hace frío\", en francés se usa \"il fait froid\", pero recuerda que en francés el sujeto \"il\" es obligatorio y nunca se puede omitir.",
      "sentence": "Il fait froid ce matin",
      "translation": "Hace frío esta mañana"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Para preguntar por el clima, se usa \"quel temps\" (qué tiempo). En preguntas, el pronombre \"il\" suele invertirse y colocarse después del verbo \"fait\", separado por un guion.",
      "sentence": "Quel temps fait-il ?",
      "translation": "¿Qué tiempo hace?"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "En francés no se dice \"hace viento\", sino que se usa la expresión \"il y a\" (hay) combinada con \"beaucoup de\" (mucho) para indicar que el clima está ventoso.",
      "sentence": "Il y a beaucoup de vent",
      "translation": "Hay mucho viento"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "En francés, \"soleil\" (sol) es una palabra masculina, por lo que lleva el artículo \"le\". Además, el pronombre \"je\" (yo) pierde su vocal y se contrae con apóstrofo frente a verbos que empiezan con vocal, como \"aime\".",
      "sentence": "J'aime le soleil",
      "translation": "Me gusta el sol"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "El verbo \"pleuvoir\" (llover) es impersonal. A diferencia del español donde decimos simplemente \"llueve\", en francés siempre debes iniciar la oración con el pronombre \"il\": \"il pleut\".",
      "sentence": "Il pleut aujourd'hui",
      "translation": "Llueve hoy"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "sentences": [
    {
      "explanation": "En japonés, \"hoy\" se dice 今日 (kyou). La partícula は (wa) marca \"hoy\" como el tema principal de la oración, indicando literalmente \"en cuanto a hoy\".",
      "sentence": "今日は忙しいです",
      "translation": "Hoy estoy ocupado"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "明日 (ashita) significa \"mañana\". A diferencia del español, en japonés no necesitamos preposiciones de tiempo (como \"en\" o \"por\") con palabras relativas al tiempo; simplemente se colocan al principio o antes de la acción.",
      "sentence": "明日学校に行きます",
      "translation": "Mañana voy a la escuela"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "昨日 (kinou) significa \"ayer\". Como la acción ocurrió en el pasado, el verbo します (shimasu - hacer) cambia a su forma pasada しました (shimashita - hice).",
      "sentence": "昨日は勉強しました",
      "translation": "Ayer estudié"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Usar 朝 (asa), que significa \"mañana\" (parte del día), junto con la partícula は (wa) indica una costumbre. Literalmente dice \"en cuanto a la mañana, tomo café\".",
      "sentence": "朝はコーヒーを飲みます",
      "translation": "En la mañana tomo café"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "夜 (yoru) significa \"noche\". No se usa ninguna palabra equivalente a \"en la\" para decir \"en la noche\", solo la palabra 夜 (yoru) seguida de su marcador de tema o contexto.",
      "sentence": "夜はテレビを見ます",
      "translation": "En la noche veo la televisión"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Para decir \"ayer en la noche\" o \"anoche\", usamos 昨日の夜 (kinou no yoru). La partícula の (no) conecta ambos sustantivos, significando literalmente \"la noche de ayer\".",
      "sentence": "昨日の夜は寒かったです",
      "translation": "Ayer en la noche hizo frío"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Al preguntar por planes futuros se usa 明日 (ashita). La partícula か (ka) al final convierte la oración en pregunta, funcionando como los signos de interrogación en español.",
      "sentence": "明日は何をしますか？",
      "translation": "¿Qué vas a hacer mañana?"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "今日の夜 (kyou no yoru) combina \"hoy\" y \"noche\" usando la partícula de posesión の (no) para decir \"la noche de hoy\" o \"esta noche\".",
      "sentence": "今日の夜はレストランに行きます",
      "translation": "Hoy en la noche voy a un restaurante"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "sentences": [
    {
      "explanation": "In Chinese, the sentence structure is Subject-Verb-Object, just like in English. Here, the verb 吃 (chī) means \"to eat\", and it is followed directly by the object 米饭 (mǐ fàn).",
      "sentence": "我吃米饭",
      "translation": "I eat rice"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "To turn the statement 你喝水 (nǐ hē shuǐ), meaning \"you drink water\", into a yes/no question, Chinese simply adds the question particle 吗 (ma) to the end. You don't need a helper verb like \"do\" in English.",
      "sentence": "你喝水吗？",
      "translation": "Do you drink water?"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "The verb 看 (kàn) is very versatile in Chinese. While English uses entirely different verbs like \"read\", \"watch\", or \"look at\", Chinese uses 看 (kàn) for all of these visual actions, such as reading a book.",
      "sentence": "她看书",
      "translation": "She reads books"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Chinese verbs do not conjugate based on the subject. The verb 听 (tīng) means \"to listen\", and its form stays exactly the same whether the subject is \"I\", \"he\", or \"we\" (我们 - wǒ men), unlike English where verbs might change.",
      "sentence": "我们听音乐",
      "translation": "We listen to music"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "The verb 说 (shuō) translates to \"speak\" or \"say\". Notice that Chinese verbs do not have an \"-s\" ending for third-person singular subjects; 他 (tā) simply pairs with the base verb 说 (shuō).",
      "sentence": "他说中文",
      "translation": "He speaks Chinese"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Here we see 看 (kàn) used again, but this time meaning \"to watch\" rather than \"to read\". The sentence keeps the standard Subject-Verb-Object order, and the 吗 (ma) at the end signals that it is a question.",
      "sentence": "你看电视吗？",
      "translation": "Do you watch TV?"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "sentences": [
    {
      "explanation": "In Russian, \"я иду\" (ya idu) means \"I am going.\" The preposition \"в\" (v) means \"to\" or \"into\" when followed by a destination. \"Магазин\" (magazin) doesn't change its form here because it is an inanimate masculine noun. Note that Russian doesn't use articles like \"the\" or \"a\".",
      "sentence": "Я иду в магазин",
      "translation": "I am going to the store"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "\"Это\" (eto) means \"this is.\" In Russian, you don't need a verb like \"is\" for simple present tense descriptions. \"Очень хороший ресторан\" (ochen' khoroshiy restoran) translates word-for-word to \"very good restaurant\", with the adjective \"хороший\" (khoroshiy) matching the masculine noun \"ресторан\" (restoran).",
      "sentence": "Это очень хороший ресторан",
      "translation": "This is a very good restaurant"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "\"Где\" (gde) means \"where\". \"Находится\" (nakhoditsya) literally translates to \"is located\" or \"finds itself.\" While you can just ask \"Где парк?\" (Gde park? - Where is the park?), adding \"находится\" makes it sound more natural and polite when asking for directions.",
      "sentence": "Где находится парк?",
      "translation": "Where is the park located?"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "\"Моя\" (moya) means \"my\" and is in the feminine form to match the feminine noun \"школа\" (shkola). Just like with other present tense sentences in Russian, the verb \"is\" is completely omitted, so it literally reads \"My school there\" using the word \"там\" (tam).",
      "sentence": "Моя школа там",
      "translation": "My school is over there"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "\"Мы\" (my) means \"we\", and \"сейчас\" (seychas) means \"now\". The preposition \"в\" (v) means \"in\" here, and it changes the ending of \"библиотека\" (biblioteka) to \"библиотеке\" (biblioteke) because it is indicating a location (the prepositional case).",
      "sentence": "Мы сейчас в библиотеке",
      "translation": "We are in the library now"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "\"Прямо\" (pryamo) means \"straight ahead\" and \"направо\" (napravo) means \"to the right\". Notice again that the verb \"is\" is not used in the Russian sentence \"Аптека прямо\" (Apteka pryamo).",
      "sentence": "Аптека прямо и направо",
      "translation": "The pharmacy is straight ahead and to the right"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "sentences": [
    {
      "explanation": "In Arabic, the verb \"is\" is not used in simple present tense sentences. You simply say \"the house big\" using البيت (al-bayt) for \"the house\" and كبير (kabir) for \"big\".",
      "sentence": "البيت كبير",
      "translation": "The house is big"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Adjectives in Arabic always come after the noun they describe. Because \"car\" (سيارة - sayyara) is a feminine word, the adjective \"small\" must take the feminine ending, becoming صغيرة (saghira).",
      "sentence": "سيارة صغيرة",
      "translation": "A small car"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "Nouns ending in the tied \"t\" sound (ة - taa marbuta) are usually feminine. The word for \"city\" (المدينة - al-madina) is feminine, so \"beautiful\" changes from جميل (jamil) to جميلة (jamila) to match.",
      "sentence": "المدينة جميلة",
      "translation": "The city is beautiful"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "To say \"this book\", Arabic uses هذا الكتاب (hadha al-kitab), which literally translates as \"this the book\". The adjective قديم (qadim) acts as the predicate, completing the thought \"is old\".",
      "sentence": "هذا الكتاب قديم",
      "translation": "This book is old"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "The letter ي (yaa) attached to the end of هاتف (hatif) changes \"phone\" to \"my phone\" (هاتفي - hatifi). The adjective جديد (jadid) follows it, meaning \"new\".",
      "sentence": "هاتفي جديد",
      "translation": "My phone is new"
    },
    {
      "explanation": "When an adjective describes a specific, definite noun, both the noun and the adjective must start with \"the\" (ال - al). So الباب القديم (al-bab al-qadim) literally means \"the door the old\".",
      "sentence": "الباب القديم",
      "translation": "The old door"
    }
  ]
}

{
